    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-11-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-11-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="460"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d460">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/2540<hi rend="superscript">23/35</hi>
                </note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="52" xml:id="d460fn52">Notation attached to the original: “Pencilled
                        memorandum given by the President to the Secretary of State (not dated but
                        probably written shortly after November 20, 1941)”. For draft proposal of a
                            <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi> handed by Ambassador Nomura to the
                        Secretary of State on November 20, see <ref target="frus1931-41v02#pg_755">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 755</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1941-11-20">undated</date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">6 months</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>U. S. to resume economic relations—some oil and rice now—more
                        later.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Japan to send no more troops to Indo-China or Manchurian border or any
                        place South—(Dutch, Brit, or Siam).</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Japan to agree not to invoke tripartite pact even if U. S. gets into
                        European war.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>U. S. to introduce Japs to Chinese to talk things over but U. S. to take
                        no part in their conversations.</item>
                </list>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Later on Pacific agreements.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
